{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536833"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.18,0.28,0.3,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94135"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2597"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressively worsening dysphagia to solids and unintentional weight loss of 6 kg. He reports intermittent retrosternal discomfort and occasional regurgitation but no haematemesis. He has a history of gastro-oesophageal reflux symptoms but no previous endoscopy. He takes no regular medications. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history and drinks alcohol socially. There is no recent travel. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no cervical lymphadenopathy and cardiopulmonary and abdominal examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpper endoscopy with biopsy shows a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the distal oesophagus. Computed tomography of chest, abdomen, and pelvis, and positron emission tomography demonstrate no distant metastatic disease, with focal increased uptake at the distal oesophageal lesion and small avid regional nodes. He undergoes oesophagectomy following neoadjuvant therapy. Postoperative histopathology confirms tumour extension to the adventitia. Two of five regional lymph nodes contain metastatic disease. Resection margins are clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate TNM staging classification?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T1, N1, M0","T2, N1, M0","T2, N2, M0","T3, N1, M0","T3, N2, M0"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStaging of oesophageal adenocarcinoma using the tumour\u2013node\u2013metastasis system integrates depth of invasion, number of involved regional lymph nodes, and presence of distant metastases to inform prognosis and treatment planning. Depth categories are based on histological penetration of the oesophageal wall, nodal categories on the count of positive regional nodes, and metastasis on distant spread detected by imaging or pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET3, N1, M0\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because histopathology shows invasion into the adventitia (T3), involvement of one to two regional lymph nodes (two positive nodes, N1), and no distant metastases on cross-sectional and positron emission tomography imaging (M0). This pattern corresponds to stage III disease in commonly used staging groupings and guides consideration of multimodal therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1, N1, M0\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as T1 indicates invasion limited to the lamina propria, muscularis mucosae, or submucosa and does not reach the adventitia, which is documented here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2, N1, M0\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because T2 denotes invasion confined to the muscularis propria, underestimating the depth compared with the confirmed adventitial involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2, N2, M0\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect on two counts: T2 undervalues the depth, and N2 indicates three to six positive nodes, whereas only two nodes are involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET3, N2, M0\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because N2 requires three to six involved regional nodes; this case has only two positive nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["T3 oesophageal cancer indicates tumour invasion into the adventitia.","N1 oesophageal cancer indicates metastasis to one to two regional lymph nodes.","Pathological staging after resection (pTNM) guides prognosis; T3N1M0 corresponds to stage III disease without distant metastasis."],"references":["Lagergren J, Smyth E, Cunningham D, et al. Oesophageal cancer. Lancet 2017; 390: 2383\u201396."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94135"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94135"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T17:44:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T17:47:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8505"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"